{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_278a62a3fffevL1DTfACz2W0yu","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d8759ea16001ZhuO5AhItM2PiD","parts":[{"id":"prt_d8759f3400012rWGPfdCvzXETa","messageID":"msg_d8759ea16001ZhuO5AhItM2PiD","sessionID":"ses_278a62a3fffevL1DTfACz2W0yu","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_421f3f90c7784c8584376aba","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: .. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/luigi.png\n2:    :alt: Luigi Logo\n3:    :align: center\n4: \n5: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/endpoint.svg?url=https%3A%2F%2Factions-badge.atrox.dev%2Fspotify%2Fluigi%2Fbadge&label=build&logo=none&%3Fref%3Dmaster&style=flat\n6:     :target: https://actions-badge.atrox.dev/spotify/luigi/goto?ref=master\n7: \n8: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/codecov/c/github/spotify/luigi/master.svg?style=flat\n9:     :target: https://codecov.io/gh/spotify/luigi?branch=master\n10: \n11: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/luigi.svg?style=flat\n12:    :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n13: \n14: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/luigi.svg?style=flat\n15:    :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n16: \n17: .. image:: https://readthedocs.org/projects/luigi/badge/?version=stable\n18:     :target: https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/?badge=stable\n19:     :alt: Documentation Status\n20: \n21: Luigi is a Python (3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13 tested) package that helps you build complex\n22: pipelines of batch jobs. It handles dependency resolution, workflow management,\n23: visualization, handling failures, command line integration, and much more.\n24: \n25: Getting Started\n26: ---------------\n27: \n28: Run ``pip install luigi`` to install the latest stable version from `PyPI\n29: <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_. `Documentation for the latest release\n30: <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/>`__ is hosted on readthedocs.\n31: \n32: Run ``pip install luigi[toml]`` to install Luigi with `TOML-based configs\n33: <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/configuration.html>`__ support.\n34: \n35: For the bleeding edge code, ``pip install\n36: git+https://github.com/spotify/luigi.git``. `Bleeding edge documentation\n37: <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/>`__ is also available.\n38: \n39: Background\n40: ----------\n41: \n42: The purpose of Luigi is to address all the plumbing typically associated\n43: with long-running batch processes. You want to chain many tasks,\n44: automate them, and failures *will* happen. These tasks can be anything,\n45: but are typically long running things like\n46: `Hadoop <http://hadoop.apache.org/>`_ jobs, dumping data to/from\n47: databases, running machine learning algorithms, or anything else.\n48: \n49: There are other software packages that focus on lower level aspects of\n50: data processing, like `Hive <http://hive.apache.org/>`__,\n51: `Pig <http://pig.apache.org/>`_, or\n52: `Cascading <http://www.cascading.org/>`_. Luigi is not a framework to\n53: replace these. Instead it helps you stitch many tasks together, where\n54: each task can be a `Hive query <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\n55: a `Hadoop job in Java <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop_jar.html>`_,\n56: a  `Spark job in Scala or Python <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.spark.html>`_,\n57: a Python snippet,\n58: `dumping a table <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.sqla.html>`_\n59: from a database, or anything else. It's easy to build up\n60: long-running pipelines that comprise thousands of tasks and take days or\n61: weeks to complete. Luigi takes care of a lot of the workflow management\n62: so that you can focus on the tasks themselves and their dependencies.\n63: \n64: You can build pretty much any task you want, but Luigi also comes with a\n65: *toolbox* of several common task templates that you use. It includes\n66: support for running\n67: `Python mapreduce jobs <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hadoop.html>`_\n68: in Hadoop, as well as\n69: `Hive <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hive.html>`__,\n70: and `Pig <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`__,\n71: jobs. It also comes with\n72: `file system abstractions for HDFS <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.hdfs.html>`_,\n73: and local files that ensures all file system operations are atomic. This\n74: is important because it means your data pipeline will not crash in a\n75: state containing partial data.\n76: \n77: Visualiser page\n78: ---------------\n79: \n80: The Luigi server comes with a web interface too, so you can search and filter\n81: among all your tasks.\n82: \n83: .. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/visualiser_front_page.png\n84:    :alt: Visualiser page\n85: \n86: Dependency graph example\n87: ------------------------\n88: \n89: Just to give you an idea of what Luigi does, this is a screen shot from\n90: something we are running in production. Using Luigi's visualiser, we get\n91: a nice visual overview of the dependency graph of the workflow. Each\n92: node represents a task which has to be run. Green tasks are already\n93: completed whereas yellow tasks are yet to be run. Most of these tasks\n94: are Hadoop jobs, but there are also some things that run locally and\n95: build up data files.\n96: \n97: .. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/user_recs.png\n98:    :alt: Dependency graph\n99: \n100: Philosophy\n101: ----------\n102: \n103: Conceptually, Luigi is similar to `GNU\n104: Make <http://www.gnu.org/software/make/>`_ where you have certain tasks\n105: and these tasks in turn may have dependencies on other tasks. There are\n106: also some similarities to `Oozie <http://oozie.apache.org/>`_\n107: and `Azkaban <https://azkaban.github.io/>`_. One major\n108: difference is that Luigi is not just built specifically for Hadoop, and\n109: it's easy to extend it with other kinds of tasks.\n110: \n111: Everything in Luigi is in Python. Instead of XML configuration or\n112: similar external data files, the dependency graph is specified *within\n113: Python*. This makes it easy to build up complex dependency graphs of\n114: tasks, where the dependencies can involve date algebra or recursive\n115: references to other versions of the same task. However, the workflow can\n116: trigger things not in Python, such as running\n117: `Pig scripts <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.pig.html>`_\n118: or `scp'ing files <https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api/luigi.contrib.ssh.html>`_.\n119: \n120: Who uses Luigi?\n121: ---------------\n122: \n123: We use Luigi internally at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ to run\n124: thousands of tasks every day, organized in complex dependency graphs.\n125: Most of these tasks are Hadoop jobs. Luigi provides an infrastructure\n126: that powers all kinds of stuff including recommendations, toplists, A/B\n127: test analysis, external reports, internal dashboards, etc.\n128: \n129: Since Luigi is open source and without any registration walls, the exact number\n130: of Luigi users is unknown. But based on the number of unique contributors, we\n131: expect hundreds of enterprises to use it. Some users have written blog posts\n132: or held presentations about Luigi:\n133: \n134: * `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/erikbern/luigi-presentation-nyc-data-science>`__\n135: * `Foursquare <https://foursquare.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2013) <http://www.slideshare.net/OpenAnayticsMeetup/luigi-presentation-17-23199897>`__\n136: * `Mortar Data (Datadog) <https://www.datadoghq.com/>`_ `(documentation / tutorial) <http://help.mortardata.com/technologies/luigi>`__\n137: * `Stripe <https://stripe.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2014) <http://www.slideshare.net/PyData/python-as-part-of-a-production-machine-learning-stack-by-michael-manapat-pydata-sv-2014>`__\n138: * `Buffer <https://buffer.com/>`_ `(blog, 2014) <https://buffer.com/resources/buffers-new-data-architecture/>`__\n139: * `SeatGeek <https://seatgeek.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://chairnerd.seatgeek.com/building-out-the-seatgeek-data-pipeline/>`__\n140: * `Treasure Data <https://www.treasuredata.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://blog.treasuredata.com/blog/2015/02/25/managing-the-data-pipeline-with-git-luigi/>`__\n141: * `Growth Intelligence <http://growthintel.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <http://www.slideshare.net/growthintel/a-beginners-guide-to-building-data-pipelines-with-luigi>`__\n142: * `AdRoll <https://www.adroll.com/>`_ `(blog, 2015) <http://tech.adroll.com/blog/data/2015/09/22/data-pipelines-docker.html>`__\n143: * 17zuoye `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mvj3/luiti-an-offline-task-management-framework>`__\n144: * `Custobar <https://www.custobar.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <http://www.slideshare.net/teemukurppa/managing-data-workflows-with-luigi>`__\n145: * `Blendle <https://launch.blendle.com/>`_ `(presentation) <http://www.anneschuth.nl/wp-content/uploads/sea-anneschuth-streamingblendle.pdf#page=126>`__\n146: * `TrustYou <http://www.trustyou.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2015) <https://speakerdeck.com/mfcabrera/pydata-berlin-2015-processing-hotel-reviews-with-python>`__\n147: * `Groupon <https://www.groupon.com/>`_ / `OrderUp <https://orderup.com>`_ `(alternative implementation) <https://github.com/groupon/luigi-warehouse>`__\n148: * `Red Hat - Marketing Operations <https://www.redhat.com>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://github.com/rh-marketingops/rh-mo-scc-luigi>`__\n149: * `GetNinjas <https://www.getninjas.com.br/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://labs.getninjas.com.br/using-luigi-to-create-and-monitor-pipelines-of-batch-jobs-eb8b3cd2a574>`__\n150: * `voyages-sncf.com <https://www.voyages-sncf.com/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://github.com/voyages-sncf-technologies/meetup-afpy-nantes-luigi>`__\n151: * `Open Targets <https://www.opentargets.org/>`_ `(blog, 2017) <https://blog.opentargets.org/using-containers-with-luigi>`__\n152: * `Leipzig University Library <https://ub.uni-leipzig.de>`_ `(presentation, 2016) <https://de.slideshare.net/MartinCzygan/build-your-own-discovery-index-of-scholary-eresources>`__ / `(project) <https://finc.info/de/datenquellen>`__\n153: * `Synetiq <https://synetiq.net/>`_ `(presentation, 2017) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M4xUQXogSfo>`__\n154: * `Glossier <https://www.glossier.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://medium.com/glossier/how-to-build-a-data-warehouse-what-weve-learned-so-far-at-glossier-6ff1e1783e31>`__\n155: * `Data Revenue <https://www.datarevenue.com/>`_ `(blog, 2018) <https://www.datarevenue.com/en/blog/how-to-scale-your-machine-learning-pipeline>`_\n156: * `Uppsala University <http://pharmb.io>`_ `(tutorial) <http://uppnex.se/twiki/do/view/Courses/EinfraMPS2015/Luigi.html>`_   / `(presentation, 2015) <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f26PqSXZdWM>`_ / `(slides, 2015) <https://www.slideshare.net/SamuelLampa/building-workflows-with-spotifys-luigi>`_ / `(poster, 2015) <https://pharmb.io/poster/2015-sciluigi/>`_ / `(paper, 2016) <https://doi.org/10.1186/s13321-016-0179-6>`_ / `(project) <https://github.com/pharmbio/sciluigi>`_\n157: * `GIPHY <https://giphy.com/>`_ `(blog, 2019) <https://engineering.giphy.com/luigi-the-10x-plumber-containerizing-scaling-luigi-in-kubernetes/>`__\n158: * `xtream <https://xtreamers.io/>`__ `(blog, 2019) <https://towardsdatascience.com/lessons-from-a-real-machine-learning-project-part-1-from-jupyter-to-luigi-bdfd0b050ca5>`__\n159: * `CIAN <https://cian.ru/>`__ `(presentation, 2019) <https://www.highload.ru/moscow/2019/abstracts/6030>`__\n160: \n161: Some more companies are using Luigi but haven't had a chance yet to write about it:\n162: \n163: * `Schibsted <http://www.schibsted.com/>`_\n164: * `enbrite.ly <http://enbrite.ly/>`_\n165: * `Dow Jones / The Wall Street Journal <http://wsj.com>`_\n166: * `Hotels.com <https://hotels.com>`_\n167: * `Newsela <https://newsela.com>`_\n168: * `Squarespace <https://www.squarespace.com/>`_\n169: * `OAO <https://adops.com/>`_\n170: * `Grovo <https://grovo.com/>`_\n171: * `Weebly <https://www.weebly.com/>`_\n172: * `Deloitte <https://www.Deloitte.co.uk/>`_\n173: * `Stacktome <https://stacktome.com/>`_\n174: * `LINX+Neemu+Chaordic <https://www.chaordic.com.br/>`_\n175: * `Foxberry <https://www.foxberry.com/>`_\n176: * `Okko <https://okko.tv/>`_\n177: * `ISVWorld <http://isvworld.com/>`_\n178: * `Big Data <https://bigdata.com.br/>`_\n179: * `Movio <https://movio.co.nz/>`_\n180: * `Bonnier News <https://www.bonniernews.se/>`_\n181: * `Starsky Robotics <https://www.starsky.io/>`_\n182: * `BaseTIS <https://www.basetis.com/>`_\n183: * `Hopper <https://www.hopper.com/>`_\n184: * `VOYAGE GROUP/Zucks <https://zucks.co.jp/en/>`_\n185: * `Textpert <https://www.textpert.ai/>`_\n186: * `Tracktics <https://www.tracktics.com/>`_\n187: * `Whizar <https://www.whizar.com/>`_\n188: * `xtream <https://www.xtreamers.io/>`__\n189: * `Skyscanner <https://www.skyscanner.net/>`_\n190: * `Jodel <https://www.jodel.com/>`_\n191: * `Mekar <https://mekar.id/en/>`_\n192: * `M3 <https://corporate.m3.com/en/>`_\n193: * `Assist Digital <https://www.assistdigital.com/>`_\n194: * `Meltwater <https://www.meltwater.com/>`_\n195: * `DevSamurai <https://www.devsamurai.com/>`_\n196: * `Veridas <https://veridas.com/>`_\n197: * `Aidentified <https://www.aidentified.com/>`_\n198: \n199: We're more than happy to have your company added here. Just send a PR on GitHub.\n200: \n201: External links\n202: --------------\n203: \n204: * `Mailing List <https://groups.google.com/d/forum/luigi-user/>`_ for discussions and asking questions. (Google Groups)\n205: * `Releases <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi>`_ (PyPI)\n206: * `Source code <https://github.com/spotify/luigi>`_ (GitHub)\n207: * `Hubot Integration <https://github.com/houzz/hubot-luigi>`_ plugin for Slack, Hipchat, etc (GitHub)\n208: \n209: Authors\n210: -------\n211: \n212: Luigi was built at `Spotify <https://www.spotify.com>`_, mainly by\n213: `Erik Bernhardsson <https://github.com/erikbern>`_ and\n214: `Elias Freider <https://github.com/freider>`_.\n215: `Many other people <https://github.com/spotify/luigi/graphs/contributors>`_\n216: have contributed since open sourcing in late 2012.\n217: `Arash Rouhani <https://github.com/tarrasch>`_ was the chief maintainer from 2015 to 2019, and now\n218: Spotify's Data Team maintains Luigi.\n\n(End of file - total 218 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":".. figure:: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotify/luigi/master/doc/luigi.png\n   :alt: Luigi Logo\n   :align: center\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/endpoint.svg?url=https%3A%2F%2Factions-badge.atrox.dev%2Fspotify%2Fluigi%2Fbadge&label=build&logo=none&%3Fref%3Dmaster&style=flat\n    :target: https://actions-badge.atrox.dev/spotify/luigi/goto?ref=master\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/codecov/c/github/spotify/luigi/master.svg?style=flat\n    :target: https://codecov.io/gh/spotify/luigi?branch=master\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/luigi.svg?style=flat\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/luigi.svg?style=flat\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/luigi\n\n.. image:: https://readthedocs.org/projects/luigi/badge/?version=stable\n    :target: https://luigi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/?badge=stable\n    :alt: Documentation Status\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1776092312676,"end":1776092312689}}}]}
